    {
      "text": "\n**Kiosk orders drive 2.8\u20133.1x higher attachment rates for premium LTOs versus third-party delivery**\n\n| Metric | Big Shack | Dubai Chocolate Shake |\n|--------|-----------|----------------------|\n| Avg Kiosk Attachment Rate | 8.5% | 7.2% |\n| Avg 3P Delivery Attachment Rate | 5.9% | 4.1% |\n| Gap (Kiosk Premium) | +2.6 pp | +3.1 pp |\n\nAcross the top 20 highest-volume locations, in-Shack kiosk customers show dramatically higher attachment for both premium LTOs. Big Shack attachment via kiosk averaged **8.5%** versus **5.9%** across UberEats, DoorDash, and GrubHub combined. Dubai Chocolate Shake showed an even wider gap: **7.2%** kiosk versus **4.1%** delivery.\n\nThe pattern holds consistently across all markets\u2014from New York City (5.2% kiosk vs. 2.7% DoorDash for Big Shack) to Seattle (10.9% kiosk vs. 8.3% DoorDash). Premium LTO positioning and discovery appear stronger in the owned in-Shack channel, likely due to point-of-sale visibility and reduced menu friction versus third-party app interfaces.\n\n**Action:**\n- Prioritize in-app promotions for premium LTOs to close the 3P delivery gap through push notifications and homepage placement\n- Test premium LTO bundling strategies on third-party platforms to increase basket attachment and offset their lower promotional susceptibility\n- Analyze third-party platform menu presentation\u2014consider repositioning premium items higher in delivery app sorting to increase visibility\n\n",
      "type": "text"
    }
  ],
